You&#39;re either not catching the exception thrown by the fetch request or there&#39;s code that exists after the request that is failing due to the necessary data not being retrieved. Providing a stacktrace would be useful but ultimately what it comes down to is correctly catching HTTP request failures with something like this:

    fetch(&#39;https://reactnative.dev/movies.json&#39;)
        .then(response =&gt; response.json())
        .then(json =&gt; {
          // logic to perform if the request succeeds
        })
        .catch(error =&gt; {
          console.error(error); // catching the error and handling it the way you see fit.
        }); // retrieved from https://reactnative.dev/docs/network
    
    // executing the rest of the function/program without relying on what happens 
    // in the fetch request due to the nature of promises.

On the other hand, if you&#39;re synchronizing the execution and awaiting the response to be retrieved, you should handle (in the catch probably) the possibility that the request would fail in a way that doesn&#39;t break the rest of your code.

